      <body>
         <div type="edition" xml:lang="pra-Latn">
             <p><lb n="1"/>p<unclear>o</unclear>kuḍurakasa yakhasa dhamaca<supplied reason="lost">ka</supplied>  <supplied reason="lost">dā</supplied>na</p>
         </div>
         <div type="apparatus">
             <listApp>
                 <app loc="1">
                     <lem>p<unclear>o</unclear>kuḍurakasa</lem>
                     <rdg source="bib:Nakanishi+Hinuber2014_01">pekuṇirakasa</rdg>
                     <note>The editors note: <quote>The name of the <foreign>Yakṣa</foreign>, which is read erroneously Pōkōtūraka in MASI, does not seem to be known from other sources.</quote> Once the correct reading <foreign>p<unclear>o</unclear>kuḍurakasa</foreign> is established, it becomes clear that this is the same toponym known from <ref target="DHARMA_INSKnI00064.xml">KnI0064</ref> (where it also occurs along with <foreign>māhiseka</foreign>), and that <foreign>yakha</foreign> must, contextually, be the proper name of the donor. </note>
                 </app>
             </listApp>
         </div>
         <div type="translation" resp="part:vito" rendition="class:83225 maturity:83209">
             <p>A Dharma-wheel <supplied reason="subaudible">relief</supplied>: the gift of Yakkha from Pokuḍura.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary">
             <p>The inscriptions is engraved above <ref target="DHARMA_INSKnI00094">KnI0094</ref>, in smaller and more shallow letters.</p>
         </div>
